spec: ab3151
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__, __delitem__, __contains__ dict-presence for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__setitem__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __setitem__. abc.ABC and abc.ABCMeta are class/metaclass objects; neither is a mutable mapping. The function type (<class 'function'>) does not define __setitem__ — function attributes are set via the standard instance __dict__, not via a subscript protocol on the function class itself."
    - "Key finding (__delitem__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __delitem__. Symmetric with __setitem__: no abc type defines item deletion by key. abc.ABCMeta supports class body definition and dynamic subclass registration (register()), but neither of these uses __delitem__."
    - "Key finding (__contains__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __contains__. abc.ABC: not a container; `x in ABC` is not defined. abc.ABCMeta: membership could conceivably be used to test class hierarchy (`SubClass in ABCMeta`), but Python uses issubclass() or the ABCMeta API for that — __contains__ is not defined in ABCMeta.__dict__. The function type: functions are not containers and define no `in` operator."
    - "abc.ABCMeta.__subclasshook__ and __subclasscheck__ provide virtual subclass testing via isinstance()/issubclass(), but these are class-level hooks on the metaclass, distinct from __contains__. operator.contains(ABCMeta.__dict__, '__contains__') is false."
    - "The function type has now been tested for 6 waves (652–657) in the abc group. It has returned true only for __get__ (wave 652) and __call__ (wave 656) and __repr__ (wave 655). All other dunders — __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__, __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__, __contains__ — are false. The function type is tightly scoped: it defines only the dunders essential to its role as a callable, displayable, descriptor."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — the first fully all-false wave for abc subjects since wave 653."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __setitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__setitem__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __setitem__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class — not a mutable mapping.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass that manages abstract method tracking and
#   virtual subclass registration; no subscript-assignment protocol.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: functions
#   support attribute assignment (f.x = v) via instance __dict__, but the
#   function class itself does not define __setitem__ for subscript assignment.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3151.setitem:
  description: "abc types __setitem__ dict-presence checks; wave 657"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3151

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3151001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__setitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3151002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__setitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3151003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__setitem__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __delitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__delitem__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __delitem__.
# abc.ABC: no deletion protocol; abstract base classes are not containers.
# abc.ABCMeta: supports register() to add virtual subclasses but offers no
#   subscript-deletion interface. Dynamic class manipulation goes through
#   metaclass machinery, not del obj[key].
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: the function
#   type does not define __delitem__. Function attributes can be deleted via
#   del f.attr (using __delattr__), but that is distinct from __delitem__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3151.delitem:
  description: "abc types __delitem__ dict-presence checks; wave 657"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3151

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3151004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__delitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3151005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__delitem__"], false]
    - ["ab3151006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__delitem__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __contains__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__contains__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __contains__.
# abc.ABC: `x in ABC` is not defined — ABC instances are not containers.
# abc.ABCMeta: virtual subclass membership is tested via issubclass() /
#   isinstance(), which internally calls __subclasscheck__ — a different slot
#   from __contains__. operator.contains(ABCMeta.__dict__, '__contains__')
#   is false even though `issubclass(X, ABC)` works.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: functions
#   do not define __contains__. `x in f` raises TypeError.
# The ABCMeta distinction is noteworthy: ABCMeta.__subclasshook__ and
#   ABCMeta.__subclasscheck__ provide virtual subclass testing, but these
#   are triggered by issubclass()/isinstance(), not by the `in` operator.
#   __contains__ is specifically the `in` membership protocol and is absent.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3151.contains:
  description: "abc types __contains__ dict-presence checks; wave 657"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3151

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3151007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__contains__"], false]
    - ["ab3151008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__contains__"], false]
    - ["ab3151009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__contains__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __setitem__, __delitem__, __contains__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __setitem__:  false for all 3.
# __delitem__:  false for all 3.
# __contains__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# This is the first fully all-false wave for all 3 abc subjects since wave 653.
# The function type, which broke the all-false pattern in wave 655 (__repr__=true)
# and wave 656 (__call__=true), returns false for all three methods here.
# Summary of all non-false results for abc subjects across all waves:
#   function type __get__:    true (wave 652, ab3076)
#   function type __repr__:   true (wave 655, ab3121)
#   function type __call__:   true (wave 656, ab3136)
# Everything else, including this wave, has been false.
# ABCMeta note: ABCMeta supports virtual subclass testing (__subclasscheck__,
#   __subclasshook__) and class-body registration (register()), but none of
#   these mechanisms involve __setitem__, __delitem__, or __contains__. The
#   metaclass operates at the type level, not the container level.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

